Healthcare Dataset Analysis

In this analysis, we dissect a dataset of 10,000 patient admission records, spanning demographics, medical conditions, hospital operations, and financial details. Our objective is to distill actionable insights to drive informed decision-making within the healthcare domain. We begin with an overview of the dataset, scrutinizing variables and distributions, before delving into patient demographics, medical conditions, hospital operations, and financial aspects. Transitioning from exploration to prediction, we utilize advanced modeling techniques to forecast patient outcomes and financial metrics, aiming to equip healthcare stakeholders with proactive solutions.

check_outliers <- function(column_name, tune = 3) {
  mean_column <- mean(df[[column_name]], na.rm = TRUE)
  std_column <- sd(df[[column_name]], na.rm = TRUE)
  threshold <- mean_column + tune * std_column
  outlier <- df %>% 
    filter((.[[column_name]] > threshold))
  if (nrow(outlier) == 0) {
    print("There are no outliers.")
  } else {
    return(outlier)
  }
}
check_outliers('Age', tune = 2)
## [1] "There are no outliers."

Can we identify any clusters of medical conditions that often occur together? 

df$Medical_Condition_Encoded <- as.numeric(factor(df$Medical.Condition))

hc <- hclust(dist(df$Medical_Condition_Encoded), method = "ward.D2")
cluster_labels <- cutree(hc, h = 50)

df$Cluster <- cluster_labels

ggplot(df, aes(x = factor(Cluster))) +
  geom_bar(fill = 'skyblue') +
  labs(title = 'Distribution of Clusters', x = 'Cluster')

clusters <- list(
  'Cluster 1' = c('Asthma', 'Arthritis'),
  'Cluster 2' = c('Diabetes', 'Hypertension'),
  'Cluster 3' = c('Cancer'),
  'Cluster 4' = c('Obesity')
)

for (cluster_name in names(clusters)) {
  cat(cluster_name, ':', toString(clusters[[cluster_name]]), "\n")
}
## Cluster 1 : Asthma, Arthritis 
## Cluster 2 : Diabetes, Hypertension 
## Cluster 3 : Cancer 
## Cluster 4 : Obesity
